post_cb({"22597074": {"ViewCount": "26", "Body": "<p>In my Array.h file is declared constructor:</p>\n<pre><code>  explicit Array(unsigned );   \n</code></pre>\n<p>and I'm implementing that in Array.cpp:</p>\n<pre><code>explicit Array::Array(unsigned size ): size(size) {}\n</code></pre>\n<p>And I got compile error:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22597074_22597074_0\">Only declarations of constructors can be 'explicit'</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Where is error?</p>\n", "Title": "error connected with explicit class", "CreationDate": "2014-03-23T21:06:20.583", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-23T21:22:38.900", "CommentCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "22597074", "Score": "-1", "OwnerUserId": "3452921", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_22597074_22597152_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "section_id": 5406}}, "n3337": {"so_22597074_22597152_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "section_id": 5201}}, "n4659": {"so_22597074_22597152_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "section_id": 6828}}}, "22597093": {"Id": "22597093", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The answer is in the error message. You should not repeat the <code>explicit</code> keyword in the definition. </p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-23T21:08:12.227", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-23T21:08:12.227", "ParentId": "22597074", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "648078"}, "22597088": {"Id": "22597088", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You do not need explicit in the cpp file, <code>Array::Array(unsigned size ): size(size) {}</code> should suffice.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-23T21:07:50.097", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-23T21:07:50.097", "ParentId": "22597074", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1783614"}, "22597152": {"Id": "22597152", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>According to the C++ Standard</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22597074_22597152_0\">6 The explicit specifier shall be used only in the declaration of a\n  constructor or conversion function <strong>within its class definition</strong>; see\n  12.3.1 and 12.3.2.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So you may use function specifier <code>explicit</code> only when you declare a constructor or conversion function within the class definition.</p>\n<p>As for the error message then it is ambiguous because function definitions are also their declarations.:)</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "2877241", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-23T21:22:38.900", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-03-23T21:14:03.197", "ParentId": "22597074", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2877241", "LastEditDate": "2014-03-23T21:22:38.900"}});